==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pyrrhic
<hw>Pyr"rhic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>pyrrhichius</ets>, Gr. <?/ belonging to the <?/ (sc. <?/) a kind of
war dance.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to an ancient Greek
martial dance.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ ye have the <xex>pyrrhic</xex> dance as
yet.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Pros.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a pyrrhic, or
to pyrrhics; containing pyrrhic; <as>as, a <ex>pyrrhic</ex>
verse</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pyrrhic victory</b></col> <ety>[From
<persfn>Pyrrhus</persfn>, king of Epirus.]</ety>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>a
victory in which the winning side sustains very heavy losses.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>any act supposedly benefitting the actor, for which the
costs outweight the benefits.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pyrrhic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pyrrhic
<hw>Pyr"rhic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <ety>[Gr. <?/: cf. F.
<ets>pyrrhique</ets>, fem.]</ety> <def>An ancient Greek martial dance,
to the accompaniment of the flute, its time being very quick.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[L. <ets>pyrrhichius</ets> (sc. <ets>pes</ets>), Gr.
<?/ (sc. <?/): cf. F. <ets>pyrrhique</ets>, masc.]</ety>
<fld>(Pros.)</fld> <def>A foot consisting of two short
syllables.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pyrrhicist</ent>⟦br⟧
